<div class="flex justify-between p-8">
  <div class="w-full">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-center">Patch Notes v5.0.0</h1>
    <br />

    <h4 class="text-xl font-bold">
      October 3, 2023 Â·
      <%= distance_of_time_in_words_to_now(Date.new(2023, 10, 3).in_time_zone('Pacific Time (US & Canada)')) %> ago
    </h4>
    <p><em>by: Patrick Kim</em></p>
    <br />

    <p class="border-b-2 border-black">
      Finally, a page that is not a homepage. Introducing, Patrick Kim's own blog! Creating a blog with Rails 7 with
      TailwindCSS was quite fun. It was fairly different and I enjoyed the struggles and experiences that I have gone
      through completing this.
    </p>
    <br />

    <div class="flex justify-items-start">
      <%= image_tag "data:image/png;base64," %>
      <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold m-2">New Implementations</h2>
    </div>
    <br />

    <ul class="border border-black p-4">
      <p><em>Not just a portfolio, but also a blog now, nifty.</em></p>
      <br />

      <p class="border-b-2 border-black"></p>
      <br />

      <li><strong>Blog</strong></li>
      <br />

      <p>
        <em>
          You still don't need to sign up, but if you want to comment or reply to a comment, looks like you'll need to.
        </em>
      </p>
      <br />

      <ul class="list-disc list-inside">
        <li>Blog posts' body is using TinyMCE instead of default text editor.</li>
        <li>
          Installed and configured pagy to paginate blog index page, if there are more than 10 posts, there will be a
          pagination where it lets users go to page 1 and up.
        </li>
        <li>Create new blog post button shows up only when an admin user is logged in.</li>
        <li>Blog posts are shown in the index page in descending order (Latest to oldest).</li>
        <li>
          Blog post body contents are limited in the index page to a certain number of lines, forcing users to click on
          "Read More ->" to read the rest of the blog post.
        </li>
        <li>Title and body fields have to be filled in order to create a blog post.</li>
        <li>Blog posts and blog comments belongs to a user. Dependent on destroy action of user.</li>
        <li>Blog comments also belongs to a blog post. Dependent on destroy action of blog post.</li>
        <li>
          Implemented reply system where it is a comment to a blog comment. Blog comment can be a parent to blog comment(s)
          which is known as reply. Also dependent on destroy action.
        </li>
        <li>In order to create a comment/reply, the body field needs to be filled out.</li>
        <li>
          Utilized stimulus and turbo links for comments and replies to create, edit, and delete without directing the user
          to the current page and updates in real time.
        </li>
        <li>
          When replying to a blog comment, the body will automatically fill out with "@user_name, " in order to indicate
          who the user is replying to.
        </li>
        <li>Blog comments and replies will have a timestamp of when it was posted and updated.</li>
        <li>
          Blog comments and replies have their respective identation. It will let users know which reply is for what
          comment and etc.
        </li>
        <li>Blog comments and replies will also show the username whenever they get created.</li>
        <li>
          Deleting their own comment/reply will not delete from the page, but rather, change the content to "Comment
          deleted by user" and updating the timestamp.
        </li>
        <li>If admin deletes other users' comment/reply, the content will change to "Comment deleted by admin".</li>
        <li>
          Buttons such as Edit, Destroy, Delete, Submit, Reply, and Back to blog posts are all dependent on user, whether
          they are signed in or not.
        </li>
        <li>Errors are correctly shown when something goes wrong in their respective places.</li>
      </ul>
      <br />

      <p class="border-b-2 border-black"></p>
      <br />

      <li><strong>Users</strong></li>
      <br />

      <p><em>Adding a library that helps with permissions.</em></p>
      <br />

      <ul class="list-disc list-inside">
        <li>Installed and configured Cancancan, an authorization library for Rails.</li>
        <li>All users, including non-users are able to publicly read all blog posts and comments.</li>
        <li>Logged in users are able to create, update, and delete their own comments.</li>
        <li>
          Only admin users are able to maintain all abilities for any models. Obviously, this should change to be more
          specific in the future.
        </li>
        <li>
          Only logged in users are able to make comments/replies. Logged out users will be directed to signing in form if
          they try to make a comment/reply.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <br />

      <p class="border-b-2 border-black"></p>
      <br />

      <li><strong>Testing</strong></li>
      <br />

      <p><em>Learned about coverage for testing in my last job.</em></p>
      <br />

      <ul class="list-disc list-inside">
        <li>
          Installed database cleaner to ensure every RSpec testing starts fresh with database being cleaned after every
          test. Avoids weird errors during RSpec testing locally and through the pipeline.
        </li>
        <li>Installed and configured Simplecov to help with validity of testing all the necessary code in each files.</li>
        <li>Now utilizing rails helper and spec helper.</li>
        <li>Added RSpec testing for blog post, blog comment, and user.</li>
      </ul>
      <br />

      <p class="border-b-2 border-black"></p>
      <br />

      <li><strong>Generality</strong></li>
      <br />

      <p>
        <em>
          Tiring of scrolling back up after scrolling all the way down? We got a button to help you with that. Notifications are important to let users know what went through and what did not.
        </em>
      </p>
      <br />

      <ul class="list-disc list-inside">
        <li>Installed and configured TinyMCE, an online rich-text editor for generality.</li>
        <li>
          Installed and configured Flowbite, an open source collection of UI components built with utility classes from
          Tailwind CSS.
        </li>
        <li>
          Implemented a button that helps users scroll back to the top when clicking on a button that shows up on bottom
          right of the page. This is shown on any page and pops up when scrolling down for a certain distance.
        </li>
        <li>
          Implemented notification alerts such as when something got successfully created by the user, deleted by the user,
          or if there were any errors that the user could not successfully do.
        </li>
        <li>Alerts are color coded where to two color; green means a notice in general, and red means an error.</li>
        <li>
          Alerts are shown above the navbar, temporarily shifting it so that it notifies the user which alert happened.
          Then the navbar is shifted back to its place.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </ul>
